<p>
  Modern Cantonese has merged the initials in the pairs
    \{將~<^e><:h>ts</:h>oeng</^e> vs 張~<^e><:h>ch</:h>oeng</^e>\},
    \{槍~<^e><:h>ts'</:h>oeng</^e> vs 昌~<^e><:h>ch'</:h>oeng</^e>\} and
    \{相~<^e><:h>s</:h>oeng</^e> vs 傷~<^e><:h>sh</:h>oeng</^e>\}.
  As noted by Samuel Wells in
  <@>
    《英華分韻撮要》
    | https://archive.org/details/tonicdictionaryo00will/page/n25
    | A tonic dictionary of the Chinese language in the Canton dialect
  </@>
  (1856, or 咸豐丙辰年):
</p>
<blockquote>
  "The initials {ch} and {ts} are constantly confounded,
  and some persons are absolutely unable to detect the difference,
  more frequently calling the words under {ts} as {ch}, than contrawise."
</blockquote>

<p>
  The pre-merger distinctions are remnant only in most romanisations
  of district names in Hong Kong, e.g.
</p>
<ul>
  
  <li>
    \{<:m><^e>ts</^e></:m> vs <:m><^e>ch</^e></:m>\}:
    將軍澳 (<:h>Ts</:h>eung Kwan O) and 荔枝角 (Lai <:h>Ch</:h>i Kok),
  </li>
  
  <li>
    \{<:m><^e>ts'</^e></:m> vs <:m><^e>ch'</^e></:m>\}:
    荃灣 (<:h>Ts</:h>uen Wan) and 東涌 (Tung <:h>Ch</:h>ung), and
  </li>
  
  <li>
    \{<:m><^e>s</^e></:m> vs <:m><^e>sh</^e></:m>\}:
    西灣河 (<:h>S</:h>ai Wan Ho) and 筲箕灣 (<:h>Sh</:h>au Kei Wan).
  </li>
  
</ul>
<p>
  Not all district romanisations follow the pre-merger consonants correctly though,
  e.g.~灣仔 should really be Wan <:h>Ts</:h>ai (not Wan <:h>Ch</:h>ai),
  and 彩虹 should be <:h>Ts</:h>oi Hung (not <:h>Ch</:h>oi Hung).
</p>

<p>
  Now despite the merging of those pairs of initials,
  I perceive a tendency for people to favour different consonants
  of the merger depending on the vowel which follows:
</p>


