<p>
  The \{<:m><^e>s</^e></:m> vs <:m><^e>sh</^e></:m>\} tendency
  is the strongest. I have never heard anyone pronounce 書,
    <^e><:h>sh</:h>u"</^e> (i.e.~[ɕyː]),
    as <^e><:h>s</:h>u"</^e> (i.e.~[syː]),
  and yet the vast majority of people will pronounce 石
    as <^e><:h>s</:h>ek</^e> (i.e.~[sɛːk̚])
    rather than <^e><:h>sh</:h>ek</^e> (i.e.~[ɕɛːk̚]).
  The \{<:m><^e>ts</^e></:m> vs <:m><^e>ch</^e></:m>\}
  and \{<:m><^e>ts'</^e></:m> vs <:m><^e>ch'</^e></:m>\} tendencies
  are not as strong, so for the purpose of my romanisation system
  I have decided to not use <:m><^e>ts</^e></:m> and <:m><^e>ts'</^e></:m>
  (which is why they are greyed out in the tables above).
  That is,
</p>

<ol>
  
  <li>
    For \{<:m><^e>ts</^e></:m> vs <:m><^e>ch</^e></:m>\}
    I always use <:m><^e>ch</^e></:m>,
  </li>
  
  <li>
    For \{<:m><^e>ts'</^e></:m> vs <:m><^e>ch'</^e></:m>\}
    I always use <:m><^e>ch'</^e></:m>, and
  </li>
  
  <li>
    For \{<:m><^e>s</^e></:m> vs <:m><^e>sh</^e></:m>\}
    I use <:m><^e>sh</^e></:m>
    if followed by the vowel <:m><^e>u"</^e></:m> (i.e.~[yː]),
    otherwise <:m><^e>s</^e></:m>.
  </li>
  
</ol>


<@2> Finals (韻) | finals </@2>


<=>
  <@i> (aa) | #aa | aː </@i>
  <@i> (a) | #a | ɐ </@i>
  <@i> (e) | #e | ɛː and e </@i>
  <@i> (ee i) | #ee-i | iː and e </@i>
  <@i> (or o) | #or-o | ɔː and o </@i>
  <@i> (oo u) | #oo-u | uː and o </@i>
  <@i> (œ) | #oe | œ </@i>
  <@i> (_) | #_ | ɵ </@i>
  <@i> (ü) | #ue | yː </@i>
  <@i> (m ng) | #m-ng | m̩ and ŋ̍ </@i>
</=>

<p>
  Cantonese has no R sound.
  In both my romanisation scheme and my approximations,
  the letter R only controls vowel sounds,
  and is <b>never</b> sounded as a consonant.
</p>
<.>
  Thank you to <b>J.H.</b> for pointing out that "rolled R" means trilling,
  rather than sounding R as a consonant.
</.>

<p>
  If typesetting of the characters œ~(<`>U+0153</`>)
  and ü~(<`>U+00FC</`>) is inconvenient,
  you may use the ASCII-only substitutes oe and ue respectively.
</p>

